04282nam a22005895i 9780520963283DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209632837 a10.1525/97805209632832doi  a(DE-B1597)520126  a(OCoLC)932064044  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aART0151002bisacsh04a779.0904bP35722104aThe Photographic Object 1970 /cMary Statzer. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Case Study: Photography into Sculpture -- tConversation with the Curator, Peter Bunnell -- tPeter Bunnell's Photography as Printmaking and Photography into Sculpture: Photography and Medium Specifi city at MoMA circa 1970 -- tA "New Prominence": Photography at MoMA in the 1960s and 1970s -- tExpanding Photography circa 1970: Photographic Objects and Conceptual Art -- tPanel Discussion with Ellen Brooks, Darryl Curran, and Leland Rice -- tDelightful Anxiety: Photography in California circa 1970 -- tThe Evolving Photographic Object -- tInterviews with the artists -- tNotes -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1970 photography curator Peter C. Bunnell organized an exhibition called Photography into Sculpture for the Museum of Modern Art, New York. The project, which brought together twenty-three photographers and artists from the United States and Canada, was among the first exhibitions to recognize work that blurred the boundaries between photography and other mediums. At once an exhibition catalogue after the fact, an oral history, and a critical reading of exhibitions and experimental photography during the 1960s and 1970s, The Photographic Object 1970 proposes precedents for contemporary artists who continue to challenge traditional practices and categories. Mary Statzer has gathered a range of diverse materials, including contributions from Bunnell, Eva Respini and Drew Sawyer, Erin O'Toole, Lucy Soutter, and Rebecca Morse as well as interviews with Ellen Brooks, Michael de Courcy, Richard Jackson, Jerry McMillan, and other of the exhibition's surviving artists. Featuring seventy-nine illustrations, most of them in color, this volume is an essential resource on a groundbreaking exhibition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aArt and photographyxExhibitions. 0aArtistsxInterviewsxCanada. 0aArtistsxInterviewsxUnited States. 0aPhotographersxInterviewsxCanadaxCanadaxUnited States. 0aPhotographersxInterviewsxUnited States. 0aPhotographyxHistoryx20th century. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh1 aStatzer, Mary, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016z978311066754708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520963283423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520963283.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066754-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles